From: Stephen Brodie <author@example.com>
Date: Thu, 1 May 2026
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] ALSA: usb-audio: Return true for clock validity on query failure

The Apogee ONEv2 (0c60:0017) requires a proprietary vendor init
sequence before it can respond to UAC2 clock validity queries.
Without this init sequence, the device returns an error to
uac_clock_source_is_valid(), causing the kernel to reject the
clock source and refuse to register the PCM devices entirely.

Returning true when the clock validity query fails allows the
device to enumerate normally. The device's clock becomes genuinely
valid once the vendor init sequence is sent via userspace.

This change affects only the error path where the device fails
to respond to the clock validity control request. Devices that
respond normally (success or explicit invalid) are unaffected.

Signed-off-by: Stephen Brodie <author@example.com>
---
 sound/usb/clock.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/sound/usb/clock.c b/sound/usb/clock.c
index XXXXXXX..YYYYYYY 100644
--- a/sound/usb/clock.c
+++ b/sound/usb/clock.c
@@ -276,7 +276,7 @@ static bool uac_clock_source_is_valid(struct snd_usb_audio *chip,
 	if (err < 0) {
 		dev_warn(&dev->dev,
 			 "%s(): cannot get clock validity for id %d\n",
 			   __func__, source_id);
-		return false;
+		return true;
 	}
